<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="ai-enhanced-design-systems">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>ux-ui-designer</domain>
    <summary>AI tooling for design systems: automated documentation, token scanning, Figma-to-code diffing, variant generation. Requires solid token foundation and consistent naming.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>design-systems</tag>
      <tag>automation</tag>
      <tag>documentation</tag>
      <tag>tokens</tag>
      <tag>component-library</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>AI-Enhanced Design Systems</title>
    <summary>AI tooling for scaling design systems with a solid token foundation: automated documentation generation from component source, token violation scanning, Figma-to-code diff, and variant generation. AI amplifies what exists — it will not fix an inconsistent or poorly structured system.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Documentation drifts from implementation silently; token violations accumulate as codebase grows; Figma and code desync over weeks. Automated agents (weekly doc-gen jobs, per-PR token audits) catch these before they compound. The prerequisite is a canonical token format and consistent naming — without it, agents propagate inconsistency at scale.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Design system has a solid token foundation and needs to scale component variants</item>
        <item>Documentation perpetually lags implementation — agent auto-generates from component source</item>
        <item>Design-to-code gap causes inconsistency — agent reconciles Figma tokens vs. CSS/Tailwind variables</item>
        <item>Team growing and consistency enforcement needs automation beyond manual design review</item>
        <item>Component adoption metrics are missing</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Weak or inconsistent design system foundation — AI amplifies existing problems</item>
        <item>No structured token system exists — generated variations will be arbitrary</item>
        <item>Component naming is inconsistent across Figma and codebase — AI propagates inconsistency at scale</item>
        <item>Fewer than ~30 components — automation overhead exceeds manual maintenance cost</item>
        <item>No agreed single source of truth (Figma vs. code tokens)</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="AI Amplification Principle">
      <rule>
        <statement>Before connecting any AI tooling to a design system, verify these prerequisites exist: a canonical token format (JSON/W3C Design Tokens spec), consistent component naming across Figma and codebase, and agreement on a single source of truth for tokens.</statement>
        <rationale>AI will amplify and extend the foundational structures provided to it. An inconsistent or poorly structured system fed into AI tooling produces inconsistency at scale — faster and at higher volume than manual processes.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Do not use AI design system tooling for a product with fewer than approximately 30 components. The automation overhead (pipeline setup, review gates, tool maintenance) exceeds the manual maintenance cost at small scale.</statement>
        <rationale>Automation has a fixed setup and maintenance cost. For small component libraries, manual maintenance is faster and more accurate than configuring and reviewing AI-generated outputs.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Documentation Generation Rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Run AI documentation generation on a schedule (weekly CI job), not on every commit. Commit-level doc generation creates noise and increases review burden without proportional value.</statement>
        <rationale>Component APIs change infrequently compared to commit frequency. Weekly regeneration captures meaningful changes; per-commit generation produces mostly identical diffs.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Include "do not use" examples in every AI-generated component doc. Positive examples alone are insufficient — agents default to showing only the happy path.</statement>
        <rationale>Developers need to know misuse patterns, not just correct usage. Docs without antipatterns lead to prop misuse and accessibility violations.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Token Enforcement Rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Gate AI-generated component variants behind a design review milestone before merging to the system. Never auto-merge variant additions without human designer review.</statement>
        <rationale>AI-generated variants often violate implicit design rules not captured in tokens (e.g., "buttons never have rounded corners in data-dense views"). Token compliance alone is insufficient for variant correctness.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Diff Figma component properties against code prop interfaces monthly. Timestamp both sources when diffing — Figma API data may lag code by weeks.</statement>
        <rationale>Design-to-code drift accumulates silently. Monthly diffs catch misalignment before it becomes a significant inconsistency problem requiring a migration.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Antipatterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Connecting AI tooling to a design system with no agreed single source of truth for tokens</description>
        <reason>AI will silently pick one source and ignore the other. The result is a system where Figma and code drift further apart, faster.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Auto-merging AI-generated Storybook stories without reviewing edge cases and error states</description>
        <reason>AI-generated stories default to the happy path. Error states, disabled states, and loading states are systematically missing unless explicitly prompted.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="CLI Tools">
      <list>
        <item>storybook CLI — build and serve component documentation; npx storybook init / storybook.js.org</item>
        <item>style-dictionary CLI — transform design tokens to platform-specific formats; npm install -g style-dictionary</item>
        <item>chromatic CLI — visual regression testing for design system components; npm install -g chromatic</item>
        <item>ts-morph — TypeScript AST parser for prop extraction from component source; github.com/dsherret/ts-morph</item>
        <item>figma-export — export Figma design tokens to JSON/CSS; npm package</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Key Services">
      <list>
        <item>Figma REST API (SaaS) — fetch component properties, variables, published library metadata; agent-friendly</item>
        <item>Storybook (OSS) — agent can write story files and trigger builds via Node.js API</item>
        <item>Chromatic (SaaS) — visual diff on component changes; CLI + API for CI integration</item>
        <item>Supernova (SaaS) — token sync Figma to code; design system governance; REST API</item>
        <item>Tokens Studio (Figma plugin) — token management with GitHub sync; agent can read exported JSON</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Agent Workflow">
      <rule>
        <statement>An agent can parse component source (React/Vue/Angular), extract prop APIs, generate Storybook stories or MDX docs, and diff them against Figma component properties via the Figma REST API. Variant generation requires a style-guide prompt constraining the output to known token values.</statement>
        <rationale>Unconstrained variant generation produces components that use arbitrary values. The token constraint is the design system's authority — the agent must operate within it.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Agentic Capabilities">
      <rule>
        <statement>A Claude subagent can automate the documentation and consistency-check layers of a design system: parse component source (React/Vue/Angular), extract prop APIs, generate structured Storybook stories or MDX docs, and diff them against Figma component properties via the Figma REST API. Variant generation (new component states, responsive breakpoints) is a strong agentic use case when a style-guide prompt constrains the output. Human designers must review generated variants before merging into the system.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents excel at documentation generation and consistency checking. Human design review is mandatory because implicit design rules (brand personality, visual hierarchy) are not captured in token files.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Recommended Subagents">
      <list>
        <item>Custom design-system-doc-agent — reads component source files, extracts TypeScript prop interfaces, generates MDX documentation and Storybook stories</item>
        <item>faion-sdd-executor-agent — executes implementation tasks defined for design system feature additions</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Prompt Patterns for Agents">
      <example type="good" title="Documentation Generation Prompt">
        <p>You are a design system documentation engineer. Given this React component source code and design token file, generate: (1) a Storybook CSF3 story file with: default export metadata, 3 named stories (default, disabled, error state); (2) an MDX doc page: component description, props table, usage guidelines (do/don't), accessibility notes. Do not invent new prop names. Only use what exists in the source.</p>
      </example>
      <example type="good" title="Token Audit Prompt">
        <p>Audit this component library for token usage violations: given a list of component files and a token file, flag any hardcoded color/spacing/font values that should be token references. Return: array of [{file, line, hardcoded_value, suggested_token}].</p>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="AI-Agent Gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent misrepresents union types and complex generics when parsing TypeScript prop interfaces</description>
        <reason>ts-morph or AST parsing handles complex types accurately; LLM-only prop extraction from code text makes errors on union, intersection, and conditional types.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent reads Figma API component properties and treats them as current without checking the timestamp</description>
        <reason>Figma API returns data as it exists in Figma, which may lag code by weeks. Always timestamp both sources and surface the lag in the diff report.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent triggers synchronous Chromatic visual regression runs and blocks on them</description>
        <reason>Visual regression on a component library can take 10+ minutes. Agent-triggered Chromatic runs must be async with webhook callback, not inline in a synchronous pipeline step.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent generating token suggestions based on Material Design or Ant Design defaults</description>
        <reason>Token suggestion models are trained on generic design systems. Suggestions may not fit brand personality or existing token naming conventions. Always review against actual brand guidelines.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="Best Practices">
      <list>
        <item>Establish one canonical token format (JSON/W3C Design Tokens spec) before connecting any AI tooling</item>
        <item>Use AI for documentation generation on a schedule (e.g., weekly CI job), not on every commit — reduces noise</item>
        <item>Gate AI-generated component variants behind a design review milestone; never auto-merge to system without review</item>
        <item>Track component adoption metrics via Storybook telemetry or import analysis — AI can then focus documentation effort on high-usage components</item>
        <item>Diff Figma component properties against code prop interfaces monthly; drift accumulates silently</item>
        <item>Include "do not use" examples in AI-generated docs — positive examples alone are insufficient</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/token-violation-scanner.py" purpose="Scan CSS and component files for hardcoded color and spacing values"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-doc-generator.txt" purpose="Agent prompt: generate Storybook stories and MDX docs from component source"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-token-audit.txt" purpose="Agent prompt: audit component library for token usage violations"/>
    </templates>
